To find the maximum value of $3a+b$, we first manipulate the given equation $9a^{2}+b^{2}-6a-2b=0$.

Step 1: Add 36 to both sides of the equation to complete the square.
\begin{align*}
9a^{2}+b^{2}-6a-2b+36 &= 0 + 36 \\
9a^{2}+b^{2}-6a-2b+36 &= 36
\end{align*}

Step 2: Factor the left side of the equation.
\begin{align*}
(3a-b)^{2} + (3a+b)^{2} &= 36
\end{align*}

Step 3: Recognize that the left side of the equation is a sum of squares, which is always greater than or equal to 0.
\begin{align*}
(3a-b)^{2} + (3a+b)^{2} &\geqslant 0
\end{align*}

Step 4: Solve the inequality to find the maximum value of $3a+b$.
\begin{align*}
(3a-b)^{2} + (3a+b)^{2} &\geqslant 0 \\
(3a-b)^{2} &\geqslant -(3a+b)^{2} \\
|3a-b| &\geqslant |3a+b|
\end{align*}

Since $a$ and $b$ are real numbers, we can take the absolute value of both sides.
\begin{align*}
3a-b &\geqslant |3a+b| \\
3a-b &\geqslant -(3a+b) \\
3a-b &\geqslant -3a-b
\end{align*}

Step 5: Simplify the inequality to find the maximum value of $3a+b$.
\begin{align*}
3a-b &\geqslant -3a-b \\
3a+b &\geqslant 0
\end{align*}

Therefore, the maximum value of $3a+b$ is $\boxed{0}$.

